			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Silverblade,
<br />

<br />
I bet they made one change and one change only. Removed the limitations on the fire pet spell level limit (ie: the limit beneath which a firepet would be able to select spells to cast). As the pet's level scales up, 45, 49, 60, the spell selection gets progressively better, while still blocking out special rare spells from the lineup (No EER or other 2k nukes from pets). I'm betting they want to see what happens when the pets are given "free choice" over what spells to choose, how that affects magicians and their power, and what the reprocussions might be.
<br />

<br />
With a limited mana pool, the fire pet is not free damage, and will eventually revert to melee only after a time, but only after blowing the daylights out of most mobs. Snare, Pillar of Frost.. these spells might be bad overall due to the AoE nature, but it would mean we mages have to be more cautious about how and where we fight with the pet, so as not to aggro indiff mobs. Snare on the pet might actually let us take down some melee-class mobs in PoP, instead of casters only.
<br />

<br />
P.S. Yes, pet spellcasting can be interrupted. Longer and longer cast times make that a possibility, though his channeling ability may be quite high. And, to keep in mind something. Last I rated the firepet's mana pool it was approximately 2250 pts. That's sufficient for 5 casts of Ice Comet in a row. It's possible this has been improved upon.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
